  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing light-bodied and full-bodied red wines with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Light-bodied reds like Pinot Noir and Beaujolais have delicate tannins and bright acidity, making them ideal for lighter proteins like salmon, duck, and mushroom dishes. Full-bodied reds such as Cabernet Sauvignon and Syrah contain robust tannins and concentrated flavors that complement rich, fatty meats like ribeye steak and braised short ribs. The key is matching the wine's intensity to the dish's richness to avoid one overwhelming the other.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve red wine at room temperature when pairing with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve red wines slightly below room temperature at 60-65°F for optimal food pairing results. Wines that are too warm can taste overly alcoholic and clash with food flavors, while overly chilled reds lose their aromatic complexity and tannin structure. Light reds like Gamay can be served at the cooler end of this range, while bold Bordeaux blends benefit from the warmer end to fully express their character alongside rich dishes.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing red wine with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is automatically choosing heavy, tannic red wines for all meat dishes without considering cooking method and sauce. A delicate poached chicken breast will be overpowered by a bold Barolo, while a light Chianti won't stand up to a pepper-crusted steak. Always consider the preparation method, seasonings, and sauce intensity rather than just the protein type when selecting your red wine pairing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you pair red wine with fish and seafood dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, certain red wines pair beautifully with fish, especially when the preparation includes rich sauces or grilled preparation. Light, low-tannin reds like Loire Valley Chinon work wonderfully with salmon, while Pinot Noir complements tuna and swordfish. The key is choosing reds with bright acidity and minimal oak influence, and pairing them with meatier fish or seafood prepared with earthy ingredients like mushrooms or herbs.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I choose affordable red wines that still pair well with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for wines from value regions like Portugal's Douro, Spain's Jumilla, or France's Languedoc, which offer excellent food-pairing potential at $12-20. Focus on grape varieties known for food-friendliness like Tempranillo, Grenache, and Portuguese field blends rather than prestige varieties. These wines often have the balanced acidity and moderate tannins needed for versatile food pairing without the premium pricing of famous appellations.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is red wine food pairing suitable for beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Red wine food pairing is very beginner-friendly when you start with versatile, medium-bodied wines like Côtes du Rhône or Chianti Classico. These wines have balanced tannins and good acidity that complement a wide range of dishes from pasta to grilled meats. Begin with classic pairings like Sangiovese with tomato-based dishes or Merlot with roasted chicken, then experiment as your palate develops and you understand how tannins, acidity, and flavor intensity interact with different foods.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibel text-wine-700 mb-2">What red wine alternatives work best for spicy cuisine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For spicy dishes, choose red wines with lower alcohol, bright acidity, and minimal tannins, such as Beaujolais, German Spätburgunder, or chilled Dolcetto. High-tannin reds amplify heat perception and can clash with spicy foods. Off-dry reds like some German Pinot Noirs or slightly sweet Lambrusco provide the best balance, as the residual sugar helps temper spice while the acidity cleanses the palate between bites.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long before a meal should I open red wine for optimal pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Open young, tannic reds like Barolo or Cabernet Sauvignon 1-2 hours before serving to allow proper aeration and tannin softening for better food integration. Lighter reds and older vintages (10+ years) only need 15-30 minutes of breathing time. Decanting can accelerate this process and is especially beneficial for bold reds being paired with rich, fatty dishes where softened tannins will better complement the food's texture and flavors.</p>
